                    <p><strong>Derived from:</strong> Ceramide-3 can be derived from both natural and synthetic sources. Naturally, ceramides are found in the lipid bilayers of cell membranes, including those of skin cells. However, the ceramide-3 used in skincare products is often synthetically produced to ensure higher purity, consistency, and stability. Synthetic ceramide-3 is typically produced through a multi-step chemical process that involves the reaction of a sphingoid base with a fatty acid.                    </p>                  
